\section{Results}
\label{sec:results}

\pgfplotscreateplotcyclelist{tensorstoreBarBW}%
  {fill=black!75,draw=black},
  {fill=black!55,draw=black},
  {fill=black!38,draw=black},
  {fill=black!20,draw=black},
}

The evaluation is organised in three layers: Rust (backend attribution), Python (binding cost), and vLLM (serving stack).

The Rust \textbf{SafeTensors} ladder shows explicit \textbf{sync} at the small end and explicit \textbf{io\_uring} from Qwen3-8B upward (Table~\ref{tab:rust-safetensors}), which motivates adaptive policy. The \textbf{ServerlessLLM} matrix never has sync fastest (Table~\ref{tab:rust-serverlessllm}); the comparison there is async versus io\_uring and \texttt{default}, not sync versus io\_uring.

The adaptive \texttt{default} policy uses three signals: (1) format family (contiguous SafeTensors versus partitioned ServerlessLLM), (2) total checkpoint bytes, and (3) shard or partition count. These signals are derived directly from the table patterns---they track where the empirical crossovers occur in the measured matrix. The policy is not a theoretical optimum; it is an engineering heuristic that automates the dominant regimes while accepting bounded misses on medium-scale rows.

The explicit misses are: on SafeTensors, \texttt{default} loses to explicit sync on SmolLM3-3B (3722ms vs 1332ms) and Qwen3-4B (3083ms vs 1821ms); on ServerlessLLM, \texttt{default} lags explicit async on SmolLM3-3B (3182ms vs 2391ms) and Qwen3-4B (3552ms vs 3504ms). These medium-scale misses are not hidden---Section~\ref{sec:limitations} states them explicitly. The selector still provides operational value because it correctly handles the majority of cases (5 of 6 SafeTensors rows, 4 of 6 ServerlessLLM rows) and automates the large-scale regime where io\_uring dominates.

\subsection{Rust-Layer Backend Results}

The Rust harness is the authoritative backend-attribution layer because it measures checkpoint loading directly, without Python tensor conversion or serving-engine initialisation costs. Unless stated otherwise, each matrix cell is one representative cold-cache run; Appendix~\ref{app:anchor-stats} reports five-repetition medians and min--max bands for selected anchors.

\subsubsection{SafeTensors}

Table~\ref{tab:rust-safetensors} summarises the explicit backend comparison for SafeTensors. Two regimes are immediately visible.

\begin{table}[htbp]
\caption{Rust cold-cache SafeTensors results (ms).}
\label{tab:rust-safetensors}
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lrrrr}
\toprule
Model & Sync & Async & Default & io\_uring \\
\midrule
Qwen3-0.6B & 555.28 & 1416.19 & 333.59 & 1159.24 \\
SmolLM3-3B & 1331.79 & 5802.05 & 3722.35 & 3812.35 \\
Qwen3-4B & 1820.85 & 5039.21 & 3083.18 & 2967.42 \\
Qwen3-8B & 3880.40 & 7074.40 & 3844.35 & 3172.37 \\
Qwen3-14B & 7030.25 & 13489.00 & 6138.70 & 5977.07 \\
Qwen3-32B & 15454.45 & 28763.46 & 12119.50 & 12089.05 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

For smaller eager whole-file loads, synchronous loading remains highly effective. On SmolLM3-3B and Qwen3-4B, sync is the strongest explicit backend. The ranking flips on larger multi-shard checkpoints. On Qwen3-8B, Qwen3-14B, and Qwen3-32B, \texttt{io\_uring} is the fastest explicit backend. The resulting rule is the clearest high-level heuristic in our evaluation: sync for smaller SafeTensors checkpoints and io\_uring for larger ones.

The async backend is consistently the weakest choice for SafeTensors. This matches the workload structure: whole-file shard loading benefits from strong bulk parallelism, not from scheduler-heavy fine-grained async orchestration.

