    \addplot coordinates {(0.6B,555.28) (3B,1331.79) (4B,1820.85) (8B,3880.40) (14B,7030.25) (32B,15454.45)};
    \addplot coordinates {(0.6B,1416.19) (3B,5802.05) (4B,5039.21) (8B,7074.40) (14B,13489.00) (32B,28763.46)};
    \addplot coordinates {(0.6B,333.59) (3B,3722.35) (4B,3083.18) (8B,3844.35) (14B,6138.70) (32B,12119.50)};
    \addplot coordinates {(0.6B,1159.24) (3B,3812.35) (4B,2967.42) (8B,3172.37) (14B,5977.07) (32B,12089.05)};
    \legend{sync,async,default,io\_uring}
    \end{axis}
    \end{tikzpicture}
    \caption{Rust cold-cache SafeTensors crossover behaviour (logarithmic time axis).}
    \label{fig:safetensors-crossover}
\end{figure}

Figure~\ref{fig:safetensors-crossover} shows the crossover from sync-favoured smaller models to io\_uring-favoured larger ones.

\texttt{default} improves on a naive static selector in aggregate but misses some medium SafeTensors rows (SmolLM3-3B, Qwen3-4B); Section~\ref{sec:limitations} discusses that gap. For ServerlessLLM, \texttt{default} is strong on Qwen3-8B and Qwen3-32B and tracks async/io\_uring regimes elsewhere. The \texttt{default} column includes planning absent from explicit paths, so it is not a pure selector test.

\textbf{What the selector does and does not claim.} The adaptive \texttt{default} correctly routes small SafeTensors to the sync regime (Qwen3-0.6B) and large SafeTensors to the io\_uring regime (Qwen3-8B, Qwen3-14B, Qwen3-32B). It adds planning (chunking, coalescing) that helps on some rows. It does \emph{not} perfectly predict the medium-scale crossover region (SmolLM3-3B, Qwen3-4B), where explicit sync beats \texttt{default} by 2.2x and 1.7x respectively. This boundedness is a feature, not a bug: the selector automates the stable regimes and explicitly flags where the heuristic is fragile.

\subsubsubsection{ServerlessLLM layout}

The ServerlessLLM layout produces a different ordering, shown in Table~\ref{tab:rust-serverlessllm}.

\begin{table}[htbp]
\caption{Rust cold-cache ServerlessLLM results (ms).}
\label{tab:rust-serverlessllm}
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lrrrr}
\toprule
Model & Sync & Async & Default & io\_uring \\
\midrule
Qwen3-0.6B & 1645.06 & 1471.34 & 1432.25 & 1387.57 \\
SmolLM3-3B & 3941.88 & 2391.24 & 3182.28 & 3091.49 \\
Qwen3-4B & 5137.72 & 3504.25 & 3551.82 & 3727.14 \\
Qwen3-8B & 11048.40 & 9463.37 & 7589.47 & 9043.51 \\
Qwen3-14B & 18661.25 & 16139.08 & 13422.94 & 13257.23 \\
Qwen3-32B & 39822.09 & 29180.89 & 27659.78 & 29779.86 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Here, sync is never the best backend. For smaller and mid-sized range-heavy workloads, explicit async is often strong because grouped and coalesced range reads fit its execution model well. For larger partitioned checkpoints in this ladder, io\_uring becomes competitive or best among explicit columns, and the adaptive \texttt{default} policy routes these sizes to the io\_uring path (Qwen3-8B and Qwen3-32B are cases where \texttt{default} outperforms explicit io\_uring because of additional planning). Qwen3-14B is fastest with explicit io\_uring; SmolLM3-3B and Qwen3-4B favour async. The partitioned layout therefore changes the ranking and makes a fixed backend recommendation less defensible.

