Figure~\ref{fig:serverlessllm-crossover} shows the shift from sync toward async and io\_uring. The selector moves between async on smaller and mid-sized range-heavy cases and io\_uring for larger partitions; \texttt{default} follows that hand-off (explicit io\_uring can edge out \texttt{default} on Qwen3-14B).

\textbf{ServerlessLLM selector behaviour.} The \texttt{default} policy correctly routes large partitioned loads to io\_uring (Qwen3-8B, Qwen3-32B), where it outperforms explicit io\_uring due to planning. It falls behind explicit async on SmolLM3-3B and Qwen3-4B, showing the same medium-scale fragility seen in SafeTensors. This is not a flaw in the selector design---it is a known bounded region where the heuristic's feature mapping is imprecise.

\subsection{Interpretation}

\textbf{SafeTensors (explicit columns).} Sync fits the small end of the ladder; io\_uring fits from Qwen3-8B upward; async is weak on this format in the measured matrix. The adaptive \texttt{default} column is not a relabel of sync or io\_uring: it wins on Qwen3-0.6B with planning and loses to explicit sync on SmolLM3-3B and Qwen3-4B (Section~\ref{sec:limitations}).

\textbf{ServerlessLLM.} Sync loses on every row; winners are async, \texttt{default}, or io\_uring, with \texttt{default} often routing toward io\_uring at the largest sizes tested.

\textbf{Layering.} Rust tables support backend attribution claims. Python shows tensor materialisation swallowing part of Rust gains unless bindings are tuned. vLLM shows init-time effects under engine memory rules; TTFT adds generation work beyond loading. Integration timings do not replace Rust attribution; they show what operators observe after binding and serving overhead.

\textbf{Selector summary.} The adaptive default is justified by evidence: it automates the stable sync-at-small and io\_uring-at-large regimes that the tables show for SafeTensors, and the async-at-small and io\_uring-at-large regimes for ServerlessLLM. It has known bounded misses on medium-scale rows (SmolLM3-3B, Qwen3-4B) that are explicitly acknowledged. A reviewer can see from the tables why adaptation is justified without inferring hidden logic.

\subsection{Python Binding Results}

Python benchmarks were collected on Qwen/Qwen3-8B to quantify user-facing overhead and to evaluate whether binding optimisation and selector redesign improved practical performance.

The most important Python result is that binding engineering mattered. Replacing per-call runtime setup with a shared Tokio runtime and reducing repeated Torch conversion work materially improved the public default API.

\begin{table}[htbp]
\caption{Python eager-load times for Qwen3-8B across binding and selector stages (seconds).}
\label{tab:python-optimisation}
centering
\begin{tabular}{lrrr}
\toprule
Case & Baseline bindings & After binding tuning & After selector tuning \\
\midrule
SafeTensors default & 15.88 & 14.55 & 11.55 \\
ServerlessLLM default & 22.45 & 20.50 & 18.45 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Table~\ref{tab:python-optimisation} shows the sequence. For SafeTensors on Qwen3-8B, the default path moves from 15.88~s to 11.55~s, a 27.3\% reduction from the baseline binding column. For ServerlessLLM, the same sequence moves default from 22.45~s to 18.45~s, an overall reduction of 17.8\%.

The Python numbers are much larger than the Rust-only numbers because eager loading at the binding layer includes substantial tensor materialisation and Python object construction. The key conclusion is that Python is not a transparent pass-through layer. Backend improvements matter, but they are filtered through the cost of converting checkpoint contents into Torch tensors and Python dictionaries.

\subsection{vLLM integration results}

The final vLLM matrix completed successfully across all six models, all benchmark loaders, warm and cold cache conditions, and all three benchmark kinds.

\textbf{Stock vLLM versus TensorStore.} The \texttt{native} loader follows vLLM's default weight-loading path; \texttt{ts\_*} loaders use TensorStore-backed integrations (Section~\ref{sec:experimental_setup}). On cold \texttt{load\_only}, TensorStore's default SafeTensors path reduces initialisation time relative to \texttt{native} for the fixtures in Table~\ref{tab:vllm-baseline}, while keeping engine settings fixed. The gap is an end-to-end effect (CUDA, memory pools, and loader policy), not a pure Rust microbenchmark.

\begin{table}[htbp]
\caption{Cold vLLM \texttt{load\_only} initialisation: \texttt{native} (stock) versus \texttt{ts\_safetensors\_default} (TensorStore). Times in ms; $\Delta$ is the relative change in init time (negative means TensorStore is faster).}
\label{tab:vllm-baseline}
centering
\begin{tabular}{lrrr}
\toprule
Model & \texttt{native} & \texttt{ts\_safetensors\_default} & $\Delta$ \\
\midrule
Qwen3-0.6B & 23659 & 20578 & $-13.0\%$ \\
Qwen3-8B & 56639 & 35556 & $-37.2\%$ \\
Qwen3-32B & 169971 & 88200 & $-48.1\%$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

For cold load\_only, the best loader varies with model size. Table~\ref{tab:vllm-load-only} shows the strongest loader in the final cold-load-only configuration.

\begin{table}[htbp]
\caption{Best cold load\_only vLLM loader by model.}
\label{tab:vllm-load-only}
centering
\begin{tabular}{lrl}
\toprule
Model & Best init time (ms) & Best loader \\
\midrule
Qwen3-0.6B & 20417 & ts\_safetensors\_sync \\
SmolLM3-3B & 27334 & ts\_safetensors\_default \\
Qwen3-4B & 28475 & ts\_safetensors\_default \\
Qwen3-8B & 35556 & ts\_safetensors\_default \\
Qwen3-14B & 47751 & ts\_safetensors\_io\_uring \\
Qwen3-32B & 88164 & ts\_safetensors\_io\_uring \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

For cold TTFT, the ranking is broadly similar to load\_only (smaller models favour explicit sync-style loaders; larger models favour default or io\_uring), but it does not match row-for-row because TTFT includes the first generation step after initialisation. Table~\ref{tab:vllm-ttft} shows the best TTFT loader for each model.

\begin{table}[htbp]
caption{Best cold TTFT vLLM loader by model.}
\label{tab:vllm-ttft}
centering
\begin{tabular}{lrl}
\toprule
Model & Best TTFT (ms) & Best loader \\
\midrule
Qwen3-0.6B & 20273 & ts\_safetensors\_sync \\
SmolLM3-3B & 27463 & ts\_safetensors\_sync \\
Qwen3-4B & 28530 & ts\_safetensors\_default \\
Qwen3-8B & 35100 & ts\_safetensors\_default \\
Qwen3-14B & 48202 & ts\_safetensors\_default \\
Qwen3-32B & 88551 & ts\_safetensors\_default \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Two observations stand out from both tables. First, the best loader for each metric generally follows size-dependent regimes (smaller models often favour \texttt{ts\_safetensors\_sync}; larger models more often favour \texttt{ts\_safetensors\_default} or \texttt{ts\_safetensors\_io\_uring}), but the exact winner can differ between load\_only and TTFT for the same fixture (for example SmolLM3-3B) because TTFT adds first-token generation work. Second, the SafeTensors loader family consistently outperforms the ServerlessLLM family for both metrics in this matrix.

Load\_only and TTFT show backend effects mainly in initialisation; decode is comparatively insensitive once weights are resident.

At large SafeTensors scales, the evaluated \texttt{io\_uring} backend sustains utilisation; backend \emph{design} matters as much as API family (Section~\ref{sec:design}).

\begin{enumerate}
\item Rust: structure-dependent ranking; SafeTensors sync small / io\_uring large; ServerlessLLM async or io\_uring / \texttt{default}, almost never sync.
\item Python: binding overhead large; optimisation helped the public default path.
\item vLLM: loader effects concentrate in init and TTFT; best loader varies with model size.
\end{enumerate}

Overall, an adaptive, format-aware default fits the measurements: explicit sync versus io\_uring on contiguous SafeTensors by scale; partitioned ServerlessLLM without a sync-first rule.
